               <p>WILLIAM ADAMSON. I am a <rs id="t18280221-291-viclabel1538" type="occupation">market-gardener</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-291-victim1629 t18280221-291-viclabel1538"></join>. The prisoner was in my employ, and had the care of my corn; this sack has my initials on it, and is mine - he has a wife and three children.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-291-person1630">
                  THOMAS 
                  SKITTERELL
               <interp inst="t18280221-291-person1630" type="surname" value="SKITTERELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-291-person1630" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-291-person1630" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman to Mr. Adamson. On Sunday evening I saw this sack in the stable; prisoner was there, and said, "I am going to Stamford-hill; I shall go out the back way; don't take any notice of it." I saw him go out towards Clapton; I followed him, and found him with this sack and corn, which I believe to be master's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-291-person1631">
                  ROBERT 
                  BROWN
               <interp inst="t18280221-291-person1631" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-291-person1631" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-291-person1631" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner, with the sack and corn; he said it was the first time.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I am very sorry for it.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 40.</p>
